{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489312"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:12:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:12:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"632"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/632"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.09,0.3,0.1,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109719"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/632"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92116"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1924"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41147"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109719"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right-sided weakness. He has no significant medical history as he avoids medical intervention typically, and takes only paracetamol for recent back pain. He was previously active and independent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 124/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has dense right-sided motor weakness affecting his arm, hand and leg. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 128 g/L (130-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 130 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine clearance: 13 mL/min (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT brain shows a 30 mL intracerebral haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is now 48 hours later, and a repeat CT scan shows that the intracerebral haematoma has not expanded.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate pharmacological agent for venous thromboembolism prophylaxis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Unfractionated heparin","Aspirin","Enoxaparin","Dabigatran","Warfarin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a small intracerebral haemorrhage with risk factors for venous thromboembolism (VTE), including current new immobility. Mechanical prophylaxis with intermittent pneumatic compression devices from admission is important. In addition, international guidelines suggest considering pharmacological prophylaxis after confirming the absence of further bleeding. The suggested timing of initiating pharmacological prophylaxis differs according to different guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E, a low-molecular-weight heparin (LMWH), is commonly used for VTE prophylaxis. Compared to unfractionated heparin, it offers several advantages, including once-daily dosing and a lower risk of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia. However, it is not ideal in this case, given the severe renal impairment. While a reduced 20 mg daily dose is an option for patients with severe renal impairment (creatinine clearance \u0026lt;30 ml/min), the risk of accumulation needs to be considered, particularly in this case where the bleeding risk is very high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnfractionated heparin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice given the patient\u0027s severe renal impairment (creatinine clearance 13 mL/min). No dose adjustment is required in severe renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for VTE prophylaxis after intracerebral haemorrhage and may increase the risk of haematoma expansion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDabigatran\u003C/strong\u003E is an option for VTE prophylaxis only in patients undergoing total hip or knee replacement. It is also contraindicated in severe renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is not used for VTE prophylaxis and would be contraindicated in the setting of recent intracerebral haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["LMWH is commonly used for VTE prophylaxis.","Compared to unfractionated heparin, it offers several advantages, including once-daily dosing and a lower risk of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia.","However, in severe renal impairment, a dose reduction of LMWH is required. In some cases, unfractionated heparin may be more suitable."],"references":["Yogendrakumar V, Lun R, Khan F, Salottolo K, Lacut K, Catriona G, Dennis M, Hutton B, Wells PS, Fergusson D, Dowlatshasi D. Venous thromboembolism prevention in intracerebral hemorrhage: A systematic review and network meta-analysis. Plus One. 2020; 15(6). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32579570/","Kappelle LJ. Preventing Deep Vein Thrombosis After Stroke: Strategies and Recommendations. Curr Treat Options Neurol. 2011; 13(6): 629-35. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21909622/","Sandercock PA, Counsell C, Kane EJ. Anticoagulants for acute ischaemic stroke. Cochrane Databse Syst Rev. 2015; 2015(3). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34676532/","Naidech, AM. Intracranial haemorrhage. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2011; 184(9); 998-1006. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22167847/","Dong C, Li Y, Ma Md Z. Venous Thromboembolism Prophylaxis After Spontaneous Intracerebral Hemorrhage: A Review. Neurologist. 2024;29(1):54-58. Published 2024 Jan 1. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37582632/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92116"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"632"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92116"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T17:48:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T17:50:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"632"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109719"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":